-- tSixteen. J. S. Mill, Mrs. Taylor, and Socialism -- tSeventeen. Portraits of J. S. Mill -- tEighteen. Preface to The Life of John Stuart Mill -- tNineteen. Review of Mill and His Early Critics -- tTwenty. Review of John Mill’s Boyhood Visit to France -- tTwenty- One. Introduction to Considerations on Representative Government -- tTwenty- Two. Introduction to The Earlier Letters of John Stuart Mill, 1812– 1848 -- tTwenty- Three. Related Correspondence -- tIndex of Names -- tIndex of Subjects0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBest known for reviving the tradition of classical liberalism, F. A. Hayek was also a prominent scholar of the philosopher John Stuart Mill. One of his greatest undertakings was a collection of Mill’s extensive correspondence with his longstanding friend and later companion and wife, Harriet Taylor-Mill. Hayek first published the Mill-Taylor correspondence in 1951, and his edition soon became required reading for any study of the nineteenth-century foundations of liberalism. This latest addition to the University of Chicago Press’s Collected Works of F. A. Hayek series showcases the fascinating intersections between two of the most prominent thinkers from two successive centuries. Hayek situates Mill within the complex social and intellectual milieu of nineteenth-century Europe—as well as within twentieth-century debates on socialism and planning—and uncovers the influence of Taylor-Mill on Mill’s political economy. The volume features the Mill-Taylor correspondence and brings together for the first time Hayek’s related writings, which were widely credited with beginning a new era of Mill scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aPhilosopherszGreat Britain. 0aPhilosophers' spouseszGreat Britain. 7aBUSINESS